\author{Jiaxi Wang, Harun Nuhu-Yakubu & James Robinson}

\title{BJT Amplifier Models: Bridging Theory and Practical Implementation}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The goal of this work is to design a multi-stage BJT amplifier with emphasis on high-sensitivity applications. Centered on the CE configuration, we tackle challenges in noise, parasitics, efficiency, temperature and distortion. Using LTspice analysis, we evaluate how noise affects low-level signal integrity and how parasitic elements like base resistance and output capacitance impact bandwidth and stability. We also assess efficiency, total harmonic distortion (THD) and  cascading complexities.  
\end{abstract}

\IEEEpeerreviewmaketitle
 
\section{Introduction}
\lettrine[lines=3, lhang=0.3, loversize=0.2]{C}E amplifiers, known for their significant voltage gain, are essential when low-noise signal amplification is required, such as biomedical devices \cite{Hosseinzadehlish2023}(e.g. hearing aids and implants), renewable energy systems (e.g., conditioning solar signals and wind energy harbourers), and Internet of Things (IoT) applications (e.g. sensing circuits in traffic monitoring systems). Addressing the complexity of real-life applications requires high level of pre-manufacture analysis using simulation tools, such as LTspice, to ensure the reliability of performance.

Although MOSFETs excel in switching due to high speed and efficiency, they have lower transconductance (how well a device can amplify signals) in low-power applications. BJTs are preferable for the continuous linear amplification desired in audio and RF\cite{OxfordMOSFETvsBJT}. JFETs give high input impedance and perform well in low-noise applications, however they lack the gain of BJTs, so are  less effective in power and noise intensive applications\cite{ReetaMary2024}. The MAT02, a dual matched transistor, is beneficial in these applications due to its exceptional impedance matching characteristics and low noise performance. CE configuration is suitable for a broad range of topologies, single-stage or cascade \cite{SedraSmith2004}. The foundational work for this study incorporates significant previous research, Sahay\cite{Sahay2019} and Kumar details transistor behavior relevant to BJT amplifiers, while Yang et al.\cite{Yang2020} provides simulation methods for analysing multi-stage configurations. Additionally, Saha \cite{Saha2024}  presents advanced transistor modeling methods.



\maketitle

\section*{Circuit Design and Methodology}

