\subsection*{1. Calculating \( r_{be} \)}

The base-emitter small-signal resistance, \( r_{be} \), represents how much the base-emitter voltage \( V_{BE} \) changes with a change in base current \( I_B \) \cite{transistor_notes2024}. \( r_{be} \) is the dynamic or incremental resistance at the base-emitter junction. 
 
\begin{equation}
r_{be} = \frac{\partial V_{BE}}{\partial I_B} \approx  200 + (1 + \beta) \frac{V_T}{I_C}
\label{eq:small_signal_rbe}
\end{equation} 


 In the small-signal analysis\cite{PangLecture6}, the calculations are simplified by concentrating on the small AC signals and ignoring the larger DC bias\cite{VajpeyiLecture}.  This relationship is derived from the Shockley equation:
\begin{equation}
I_C = I_S \left( e^{\frac{V_{BE}}{V_T}} - 1 \right)\cite{LeGoff2023}
\label{eq:shockley}
\end{equation}


When \( V_{BE} \) changes slightly from an operating point, we can expand \( e^{\frac{V_{BE}}{V_T}} \) in a Taylor's series \cite{Pivnev2014}. For small values of \( \Delta V_{BE} \), the exponential behavior of the function can be approximated as linear\cite{LailiLecture}, the higher-order terms in the series become negligible, as is usually expected with Taylors series':

\begin{equation}
I_C \approx I_C(Q) + \left( \frac{I_S}{V_T} e^{\frac{V_{BE}}{V_T}} \right) \Delta V_{BE}
\label{eq:linearized_current}  \cite{Shockley1950}
\end{equation}



This approximation comes from the exponential dependence of \( I_C \) on \( V_{BE} \) in the Shockley equation, where \( V_T \) (the thermal voltage) represents the change in voltage needed to change the current by a factor of \( e \). The factor \( (1 + \beta) \) reflects the gain of the transistor, showing that as the current gain \( \beta \) increases, \( r_{be} \) also increases.

Given in the MAT02–Specifications \cite{AnalogDevices2004}, \( \beta = 500 \), \( V_T = \SI{26}{\milli\volt} \), and \( I_C = \SI{20}{\milli\ampere} \).

\begin{equation}
r_{be} = 200 + (1 + 500) \times \frac{26 \times 10^{-3}}{20 \times 10^{-3}} = 851 \, \Omega
\end{equation}

This value for \( r_{be} \) will effect the magnitude of input signal voltage required to drive the transistor to a specific base current.


\subsection*{2. Voltage Gain \( A_v \)}

\( A_v \) of a common-emitter amplifier is given by:
\begin{equation}
A_v = \beta \frac{R_3 \parallel R_5}{r_{be}}
\end{equation}

Given \( A_v = 20 \), \( \beta = 500 \), and \( r_{be} = 851 \, \Omega \), solving for \( R_3 \) gives:
\[
R_3 \approx 34.21 \, \Omega
\]


From theoretical calculations we discover that R3 has a value of (34.21$\Omega$) but the actual component has a value of (25$\Omega$), hence requiring us to fine-tune by using altered simulations, sweeping and biasing conditions. \( I_{CQ} \) and gain values were cross-checked with both the MAT02 datasheet and the SPICE model because the SPICE model showed differences in parameters such as \( R_{be} \) compared to datasheet specifications.

To enhance circuit stability \cite{VSSUT} and ensure a more reliable gain predictions,  \( R_3 \) could be increased. The biasing network could be adjusted as a higher \( R_3 \)  reduces the instability with the sensitive \( R_4 \) values \cite{Ben Mabrouk}.


 


 {4. Determining \( V_{BQ} \) with Voltage Divider}

The voltage \( V_{BQ} \) is a result of the voltage divider formed by \( R_1 \) and \( R_2 \), shown as:

\begin{equation} 
V_{BQ} = \frac{R_2}{R_1 + R_2} \times V_{CC}
\end{equation}

where \( V_{CC} \) is 12 V, and \( V_{BQ} \) is 3 V.


The selection of biasing network involves choosing \( R_1 = 10 \, \text{k}\Omega \) and \( R_2 = 30 \, \text{k}\Omega \).  The base voltage \( V_B \) is set and the transistor is placed in its active region to ensure the current is 10–20 times greater in magnitude than \( I_B \). It also prevents loading effects \cite{AnalogDevices}, keeping \( V_B \) stable regardless if variations in \( \beta \). Power conservation is discovered by using high-value resistors to reduce current flow in the divider network. Lower resistor values lead to greater power losses and potential thermal runaway( the illimitable process where the increase in temperature of the system leads to more energy being relased and the temperature increasing further),due to increased \( I_C \) with temperature. This pushes the transistor out of the desired operating region. Standard resistor values like \( 10 \, \text{k}\Omega \) and \( 30 \, \text{k}\Omega \) are part of the E12 and E24 series \cite{ccea_resistors}, making them readily available and allowing the design to be simplified.





 

{5. Calculating \( I_{CQ} \) (or \( I_{EQ} \)) and \( R_4 \)}

\( R_4 \) is designed so that it meets the particular value\( I_{CQ} = 20~\si{\milli\ampere} \). It increases the transistor’s allowance for input signals, allowing it to stay in the active region over a wider bandwidth of input voltages. By preventing the transistor from entering saturation or cutoff, this operating point reduces the risk of nonlinear distortion and improves the accuracy. 

\begin{equation} % 1. Transconductance gm
g_m = \frac{I_{CQ}}{V_T} \quad \text{(where } V_T \approx 26~\text{mV} \text{)}
\end{equation} 


The measured transconductance (\(g_m\)) of the transistor is 0.385 S, this is a significantly high value under the given operating conditions. This matches the general expectation of typical BJT transconductance values. 
“are approximately 40 mS for a 1-\(\mu\)A collector current at room temperature\cite{transconductance2024}."

This higher \( I_{CQ} \) also reduces the effects of parasitic capacitances (such as \( C_{bc} \) and \( C_{be} \)), improving the transistor’s response to high-frequency signals. 



\begin{equation}
I_{CQ} = I_{EQ} = \frac{V_{BQ} - V_{BEQ}}{R_4}
\end{equation}

Given:
\( V_{BEQ} = 0.7 \, \text{V} \),
 \( I_{CQ} = \SI{20}{\milli\ampere} \),
\( V_{BQ} = \SI{3}{\volt} \)

 
\begin{equation}
R_4 = \frac{3 - 0.7}{20 \times 10^{-3}} = 115 \, \Omega
\end{equation}

Selecting \( R_4 = 199 \, \Omega \) proved to be a more effective choice, since it reduces \( I_C \) from 20 mA to 11 mA resulting in a slight decrease in \( g_m \), which is within the recommended limits of safe operating range found in the data booklet.  This prevents overheating or potential damage from extended use. This is because \( A_V \) of a CE amplifier is proportional to the transistor's transconductance \( g_m \), 
\begin{equation}
\quad A_V \propto g_m \cite{purdueBJT2024}
\end{equation}

 
In practical applications, preventing an unchecked cycle,where increasing temperature increases current, emphasises temperature is important for reliability. It is suitable for environments with fluctuating conditions and those that require lower power consumption like sound systems. 
 

 





\section{Calculation}


\subsection{DC simulation and the operating voltages across the
base (VB), collector (VC) and emitter(VE).}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Base Voltage (\( V_B \))}: 8.29 V
    \item \textbf{Collector Voltage (\( V_C \))}: 11.04 V
    \item \textbf{Emitter Voltage (\( V_E \))}: 7.63V (expected VE =3.7 V)

\end{itemize}

\subsection{Theoretical Calculations}

\paragraph{\( V_E \)}
With a small emitter resistance of \( 199 \, \Omega \), the high \( V_E \) value suggests that the \( I_E \) must be considerably larger in the simulation than in the theoretical expectations.  
\begin{equation}
V_E = I_E \times R_E
\end{equation}


\textbf{Higher Emitter Current}: An elevated \( V_B \) increase \( I_E \)\cite{Hunter}, as \( I_E \) is sensitive to \( V_{BE} \), this would proportionally boost \( I_E \) according to:
\begin{equation} 
I_E \approx I_C + I_B \cite{Kumar2024}
\end{equation} 

 \textbf{Base-Emitter Voltage \( V_{BE} \)}: observed in the simulation close to the typical assumption for silicon transistors. Assuming the base-emitter junction acts like a forward-biased diode, the expected voltage drop \( V_{BE} \approx 0.7 \, \text{V} \) to turn on and start conducting significantly \cite{Carnegie1999}. 

\begin{equation}
V_{BE} = V_B - V_E = 8.29  \, \text{V} - 7.63 \, \text{V} = 0.66 \, \text{V} \end{equation} 

A positive \( V_{BE} \) as expected for normal operation in an NPN transistor \cite{MITOCW2006}. This bias allows charge carriers (electrons) to overcome the junction's barrier potential, enabling current flow from the emitter to the base.

 
\paragraph{ The base-collector voltage}
\begin{equation}
V_{BC} = V_B - V_C = 8.29 \, \text{V} - 11.04 \, \text{V} = -2.75 \, \text{V}
\end{equation} 
A negative \( V_{BC} \) confirms that the base-collector junction is reverse-biased \cite{Hu2020}, consistent with active-region , where the collector is more positive than the base. This prevents charge carriers from moving from the base to the collector.


