\section*{Voltage Gain Calculation}

To determine \( A_V \) of the amplifier, a transient analysis was conducted in LTspice with a directive of \texttt{tran 0.01}, allowing observation of both input and output waveforms. 

\begin{itemize}
    \item Output peak-to-peak voltage, \( V(\text{out}) = 406.82 \, \text{mV} \)
    \item Input peak-to-peak voltage, \( V(\text{in}) = 19.77 \, \text{mV} \)
\end{itemize}
\begin{equation} 
A_V = \frac{V(\text{out})}{V(\text{in})} = \frac{406.82}{19.77} = 20.57
\end{equation}

\begin{equation} 
\text{Gain (dB)} = 20 \times \log_{10}(A_V) \approx 26.3 \, \text{dB}
\end{equation}


\subsection*{Verification of Signal Integrity}
The input waveform was compared against the output voltage waveform to ensure that the output signal was free from distortion or clipping and remained within the power supply limits. Two corrective steps were considered:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item  {Reduction of the Input Signal Amplitude so the output was held within the operational range of the amplifier}
   
    \item  {Adjusting Transistor Biasing in case the \(Q\)-point is too close to the supply limits, part of the input signal’s swing may push the output beyond these limits.} 
    

\end{enumerate}
 

% Calculation of Input Impedance (Z_{in}) and Output Impedance (Z_{out})

\section*{Calculation of Input Impedance (\(Z_{\text{in}}\))}

To calculate the input impedance \( Z_{\text{in}} \) of the BJT circuit,   consider the resistors \( R_1 \), \( R_2 \), \( r_{be} \), and \( R_4 \) in parallel:

\begin{equation}
Z_{\text{in}} = R_1 \parallel R_2 \parallel (r_{be} + \beta R_4) \cite{ElectronicsTutorials2024}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
Z_{\text{in}} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{R_1} + \frac{1}{R_2} + \frac{1}{r_{be} + \beta R_4}} \approx 6979.39 \, \Omega
\end{equation}

Thus, the input impedance \( Z_{\text{in}} \) is approximately \( 6979.39 \, \Omega \).

\section*{Calculation of Output Impedance (\(Z_{\text{out}}\))}

The output impedance of an amplifier is described by the effective impedance seen by the load when observed from the amplifier’s output, with the input signal set to zero to isolate output behavior. For a BJT amplifier, this value is calculated by examining the small-signal equivalent circuit.  

\begin{equation}
Z_{\text{out}} = \frac{V_{CE}}{I_C}= R_C \parallel R_L \cite{ElectronicsTutorials2024}
\end{equation}

 



\begin{equation}
Z_{\text{out}} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{R_C} + \frac{1}{R_L}} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{25} + \frac{1}{10,500}} \approx 24.94 \, \Omega
\end{equation}


\section*{Importance of Impedance Matching in Real-World}


The $Z_{\text{in}}$ of $6979 \, \Omega$ is relatively high, which is advantageous for interfacing with sources such as sensor outputs\cite{WMPhysicsLab}. This high  $Z_{\text{in}}$  minimises the current drawn from the preceding stage, thereby allowing a greater portion of the source voltage to appear across the input terminals.  In \textbf{wireless communication}, (mobile phones and Wi-Fi systems), the antenna must be matched to the impedance of the transmitter and receiver circuits to prevents signal strength degradation.

For \textbf{medical imaging} ultrasound machines, the impedance of the transducer must match that of the human body. If it does not the ultrasound waves would reflect back rather than penetrate the body, preventing proper imaging. Ultrasound gel is applied between the transducer and the skin to bridge the impedance difference\cite{MDPI2024}.

In \textbf{RF applications}, the ideal case $Z_{\text{out}} = Z_{\text{load}}$ ensures maximum power transfer and minimises reflection losses,if they are not equal only a fraction of the power reaches the load, resulting in signal reflections which leads to standing waves and signal cancellations. On the contrary, the $Z_{\text{out}}$ of \(24.94 \, \Omega\) is low, which is particularly beneficial for driving subsequent stages or loads as low $Z_{\text{out}}$ minimises the voltage drop across the amplifier’s output, thereby allowing more of the signal voltage to reach the load. 


\section{Characterisation of the Amplifier Circuit for 20 dB Voltage Gain}

\subsection{Parameter Sweep of Load Resistor (R5)}


 The step size of 300 \(\Omega\) is small enough to capture subtle variations in gain and stability, yet broad enough to avoid redundancy in output data, capture performance across minimal load, mid-range, and realistic high-impedance load conditions.




\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{varying_resistance.png}
    \caption{Output voltage waveform of \(\texttt{.step}\) param \( R5 \) from 10 to 20k with 300 steps 
(.step \, \text{param} \, R5 \, 10 \, 20k \, 300)}
    \label{fig:output_waveform}
\end{figure}



\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Increasing \( R5 \):} results in a greater voltage drop across the resistor, gain increases as \( R5 \) rises due to a reduced load on the output, allowing for a higher output voltage swing. However, too large a resistor (beyond 40 k\(\Omega\)) push the transistor toward saturation, causing output distortion.
    \item \textbf{Decreasing \( R5 \):} reduces the gain as the load becomes heavier on the transistor, limiting the output swing. If \( R5 \) drops below 500\(\Omega\), the gain will recuce significantly as the amplifier's output struggles to drive the heavier load.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{3. Effect of Bypass Capacitor \( C3 \) on Gain}


The impedance of the capacitor decreases with frequency, shorting R4 for AC signals, which increases the voltage gain. For DC, the capacitor behaves as an open circuit, so the DC biasing is determined by R4\cite{SedraSmith2024}.  


\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.15\textheight]{varying_capacitance_waveform}
    \caption{Vout of varying the capacitance \texttt{.step param C3 1u 200u 10u}}
    \label{fig:varying_capacitance_waveform}
\end{figure}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Higher \( C3 \) (e.g, 100 µF):} Allows more low frequencies to be bypassed, increasing gain by minimising emitter degeneration due to bypassing of \( r_e \). Observation suggests that at huge values, the effect becomes negligible.
    \item \textbf{Lower \( C3 \) (e.g, 10 µF):} Leads to a more pronounced high-pass effect, as emitter degeneration is more effective at low frequencies.
\end{itemize}






\section{Feedback Network in Amplifiers}

 \textbf{Rf} provides \textbf{DC feedback}, and \textbf{Cf} provides \textbf{AC feedback}. The larger the feedback resistor \( R_f \) (↑), the more signal is fed back to the base, leading to a \textbf{greater reduction in gain} (↓). This negative feedback in system \textbf{linearise the amplifier} by "correcting" the signal, making the output more proportional to the input, reducing harmonic distortion. This results in a cleaner, more accurate amplification of the input signal\cite{AllAboutCircuitsFeedback}.


\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Schematic Diagram of the Amplifier Circuit with Feedback Network.png}
    \caption{Schematic Diagram of the Amplifier Circuit with Feedback Network}
    \label{fig:schematic}
\end{figure}


MAT02 is a dual matched NPN transistor with exceptionally low offset voltage and low noise\cite{AnalogDevicesMAT02}. \( R_f = 470\text{k}\Omega \) and \( C_f = 10\text{pF} \) would provide mild frequency-dependent feedback, reducing gain at high frequencies. Without feedback, a 1 MHz input signal produce a Total Harmonic Distortion (THD) around 5\% due to the transistor's non-linear behavior. With feedback, the THD can be reduced down to 1\%.

\textbf{DC Isolation for the Feedback Path}
    
    The presence of \( C_2 \) allows the feedback network to focus purely on AC feedback effects. The placement of \( R_f \) after \( C_2 \) causes the feedback path to be in isolation from the DC bias of the collector. Since \( R_f \) connects to the base of the transistor, linking it directly to the collector without \( C_2 \) would allow the DC operating point at the collector to influence the base directly. This would disrupt the stable biasing set by \( R_1 \) and \( R_2 \) at the base. With \( C_2 \) in place, \( R_f \) only provides AC feedback to the base, preserving the DC biasing of the transistor.
 


\section*{1. Feedback Resistor \( R_f = 470\text{k} \Omega\)}

A higher \( R_f \) value means less current flows back into the base, resulting in weaker feedback and thus a smaller reduction in gain.
Lower values, such as \( 100 \, \text{k}\Omega \), would reduce the gain too much, while higher values, such as \( 1 \, \text{M}\Omega \) have a weak effect. The chosen \( R_f \) value fits well with the amplifier's resistor values, maintaining \( \beta \) for moderate gain control. 
 

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.14\textheight]{Frequency Response of BJT Amplifier with Negative Feedback Network (Rf-Cf)}
    \caption{Frequency Response  with Negative Feedback Network (Rf-Cf)}
    \label{fig:frequency_response}
\end{figure}

\section{Frequency Response Analysis}
   
 

At low frequency, the feedback effect is small, so the amplifier retains most of its open-loop gain due to the high-pass filtering effect\cite{DoeeetCapacitors}. The gain is significantly weakened because coupling capacitors block DC components and low-frequency signals. Above 100MHz, the gain is increasingly reduced due to feedback, causing a roll-off in high-frequency response. This cutoff frequency is ideal for applications where the amplifier needs to maintain its gain at low and mid frequencies (up to around 20-30kHz in audio or precision signal applications\cite{NCUFeedbackLecture}) but roll off at higher frequencies to limit noise and ensure stability. The 10pF capacitor avoids excessive feedback at frequencies below the cutoff through trial and error.

 

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Gain Plateau}: The frequency response reaches a flat region where the gain stabilizes around 24 dB (the passband),  indicating  from 10 kHz to 50 MHz), the amplifier is effectively amplifying the input signal without significant attenuation or phase distortion. \( R_f \) provides negative feedback to stabilise the DC operating point, reducing variations in gain due to transistor parameter fluctuations. At mid-frequencies, \( C_f \)  starts to act as a bypass around \( R_f \)  to maintain higher gain in this range, as the negative feedback from \( R_f \) alone is partially cancelled.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{High-Frequency Roll-Off}
This decline begins around 50 MHz and prominent approaching GHz range. \( C_f \)  now acts as a near-short across \( R_f \), introducing a low-impedance path for higher frequencies. This increases negative feedback. At high frequencies, the internal parasitic capacitances of the MAT-02 transistor contribute to the roll-off by introducing additional poles in the frequency response, compounding the effect of \( C_f \).


\subsection{Phase Shift at High Frequencies}
\begin{itemize}
    \item  the phase shift moves beyond -360°, indicating multiple phase shifts contributed by each pole introduced by the feedback network and parasitic elements. The network \( (R_f-C_f) \) produces a lead-lag response, exacerbates phase lag at high frequencies. 
\end{itemize}


 


\section*{\textbf{Analysis of Temperature Stability in Common-Emitter Amplifier Circuit}}

The results indicate minimal variation in the bias voltages \( V_b \) (base), \( V_c \) (collector), and \( V_e \) (emitter) across the simulated temperature range from -50°C to 50°C.  The close proximity of traces indicates that the circuit is relatively temperature-stable.

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{temperature_stability} % Replace with the actual path
    \caption{Temperature Variation Effect on Bias Voltages through Sweep Analysis.}
    \label{fig:temperature_stability}
\end{figure}
A stable external 12V supply (VCC) is used, limiting temperature-induced shifts primarily to internal transistor effects.

 
 \textbf{Effect of Emitter Degeneration (R4):}

\begin{itemize}
    \item The \( R_4 = 199 \, \Omega \) counteracts changes in the \( I_C \) due to temperature fluctuations. As temperature increases, the \( V_{BE} \) decreases, which would typically increase \( I_C \). The voltage across \( R_4 \) rises with increased current, reducing the \( V_{BE} \)\cite{ThermalStability}.
\end{itemize}


\textbf{Large Capacitance Values:}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Large capacitance values (100~\(\mu\)F) enhance stability against high-frequency variations and transient shifts.
\end{itemize}


  
 
\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{AC_response_temp_sweep} % Replace with your actual image filename
    \caption{Voltage gain of Common-Emitter Amplifier with Temperature Sweep}
    \label{fig:AC_response_temp_sweep}
\end{figure}

 

\subsection*{Voltage Gain Characteristics}
The graph shows the voltage gain \( \frac{V_{\text{out}}}{V_{\text{in}}} \) plotted in decibels (dB) as a function of frequency. The gain remains relatively stable in the mid-frequency range but decreases sharply at higher frequencies, indicating the cutoff or bandwidth limit. 


\subsection*{Observations from the Graph}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Mid-Frequency Gain}: The solid magenta line indicates a stable gain at mid-frequencies, suggesting minimal temperature effects in this range.
    \item \textbf{High-Frequency Drop}: The sharp decline in gain at higher frequencies becomes more pronounced as temperature increases, reduced current gain.
    \item \textbf{Low-Frequency Stability}: The gain is stable again at low frequencies, where temperature effects are less significant due to minimal reactive influences.
\end{itemize}
\section*{Importance of Thermal Stability and Compensation Techniques}

\subsection*{Base-Emitter Voltage (\( V_{BE} \))}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Temperature Dependence}: The \( V_{BE} \) typically decreases by approximately 2 mV for each 1°C increase in temperature\cite{TITemperatureCoefficient}.
    \item \textbf{Explanation}:  As the temperature rises, the intrinsic carrier concentration in silicon increases due to thermal excitation, reducing the energy barrier for carrier movement. This results in a lower \( V_{BE} \) required to forward-bias the junction\cite{ScienceDirectEmitterJunction}.Models such as the Ebers-Moll\cite{OregonStateHSpice} describe the DC behavior of transistors and include temperature-dependent parameters like thermal voltage (\( V_T \)) and saturation current (\( I_S \)).
\end{itemize}



\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Adding \( R_E \) for negative feedback.}
    \item \textbf{Thermally Stable Components\cite{MetalFilmResistors}}:Metal Film Resistors and Precision Transistors 
    \item \textbf{Heat Sinks}: Aluminum Heat Sink\cite{BJTHeatSink}
    \item \textbf{Miller Compensation}: Miller capacitor \cite{MillerLecture} helps manage high-frequency behavior and mitigate phase distortion, which can be worsened by temperature-dependent parasitic effects.
 
\end{itemize}
 



\section{Analysis of Noise Sources and Their Impact on Output Performance}
\label{sec:noise_analysis}

 
\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.14\textheight]{Output Noise Voltage Density vs. Frequency for Common-Emitter Amplifier} % Replace with your image file name
    \caption{Output Noise Voltage Density vs. Frequency for Common-Emitter Amplifier}
    \label{fig:output_noise}
\end{figure}
 

\textbf{Blue Trace (Output Noise Voltage Density):} Below 100 Hz, the output noise voltage density is low but increases with frequency, peaking between 15 kHz and 5 MHz. Beyond 10 MHz, the noise density decreases, showing a roll-off.

\textbf{Green Trace (Input-Referred Noise):} Represents the noise equivalent at the input that causes the observed output noise.  




\subsection*{Observations from the Graph}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Low-Frequency Behavior (Below 10 kHz)}:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The input-referred noise \( V_{\text{inoise}} \) is significant at lower frequencies due to flicker noise (1/f noise).
        \item The output noise \( V_{\text{onoise}} \) is minimal, suggesting reduced amplification or circuit filtering .
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Mid-Frequency Range (10 kHz to 1 MHz)}:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The output noise voltage stabilises, showing that thermal noise \( V_n = \sqrt{4k T R \Delta f} \)\cite{ThermalNoiseEquation}
 and shot noise\( I_n = \sqrt{2q I_C \Delta f} \) \cite{ShotNoiseEquation} are the main contributors.
        \item \( V_{\text{onoise}} \) peaks and remains constant, indicating the amplifier's bandwidth and band-limited behavior\cite{Cadence}.
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{High-Frequency Range (Above 1 MHz)}:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \( V_{\text{inoise}} \) increases, likely due to high-frequency noise components and parasitic effects.
        \item \( V_{\text{onoise}} \) drops as the frequency surpasses the operational bandwidth of the circuit.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Impact on Amplifier Performance}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Signal Masking}: At low signal levels, noise mask the input signal, leading to a reduced SNR.
    \item \textbf{Dynamic Range Reduction}: Noise limits the effective dynamic range of the  precision amplifier. 
    \item \textbf{Low-Frequency Performance}: Flicker noise impacts low-frequency signal clarity for audio and sensor. 
    \item \textbf{Phase Noise and Distortion}: Low-frequency noise cause phase noise, affecting timing and waveform integrity.
    \item \textbf{High-Frequency Considerations}: Rising input-referred noise at high frequencies indicates parasitic effects.
\end{itemize}


\section*{Frequency Response of the Ideal Amplifier}

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.14\textheight]{Ideal Amplifier without Parasitics.png}
    \caption{Frequency response of Ideal amplifier without Parasitics showing the magnitude (solid line) and phase (dotted line) versus frequency. }
    \label{fig:frequency_response}
\end{figure}


The peak gain observed in the plot is 24 dB. The -3 dB point corresponds to a gain of 24 dB minus 3 dB, which equals 21 dB. The lower 3 dB frequency (\(f_1\)) is 10 kHz. The upper 3 dB frequency (\(f_2\)) is 100 MHz.
 

The 3 dB bandwidth \( BW \) is defined as:
\begin{equation}
BW = f_2 - f_1 = 100 \text{ MHz} - 10 \text{ kHz} \approx 99.99 \text{ MHz}
\end{equation}



\section*{Parasitic Elements}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Base Resistance \( r_b \)}: inherent resistance in the transistor’s base region. 
    \item \textbf{Collector Resistance \( r_c \)}:internal resistance in the collector region, cause voltage drops in the output, affecting the linearity, limiting maximum output swing.
    \item \textbf{Output Capacitance \( C_{out} \)}:  across the collector-emitter junction and has a significant impact on the high-frequency response. As the frequency increases, \( C_{out} \) creates a low-pass filter effect.
\end{enumerate}

  
 \begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Impact of Real-World Transistor Parasitics on Common-Emitter Amplifier Performance.png} % Replace with the correct path
    \caption{Impact of Real-World Transistor Parasitics on Common-Emitter Amplifier Performance}
    \label{fig:transistor_parasitics}
\end{figure}





\subsection{Design for Non-Ideal Case (Real-World Model)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \( R_b = 20 \, \Omega \) in series with the base.
        \item \( R_c = 5 \, \Omega \) in series with the collector.
        \item \( C_{out} = 5 \, \text{pF} \) between the collector and emitter.
    \end{itemize}
 

The input signal flows from the through C1 and reach the
base of the transistor. Ideally a voltage drop right at input so
the base voltage is slightly lower than the voltage on the right
side of C1\cite {BJTCurrentsVoltages}.  C1 is there to AC couple the input signal to the
amplifier, blocking any DC component and allowing only AC
signals to pass. The purpose is to interact only with the AC
signal (the intended input) without affecting any DC biasing
from previous stages or the signal source.




\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.14\textheight]{real-world transistor model with parasitic.png}
    \caption{Frequency response of a real-world transistor model with parasitics, illustrating the magnitude (solid line) and phase (dotted line) versus frequency. The plot spans from 1 Hz to 10 GHz, showing the behavior of the transistor with inherent parasitic effects. The response reveals gain reduction at both low and high frequencies due to parasitic capacitances and resistance.}
    \label{fig:real_world_transistor_response}
\end{figure}



\subsection*{Explanation of Gain Drop}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Low-Frequency Drop}: Due to the high reactance of coupling capacitors the gain drops at low frequencies, limiting signal transfer.
    \item \textbf{High-Frequency Drop}: The gain reduction at high frequencies is due to parasitic capacitances (e.g. the Miller effect in transistors and the inherent frequency response limitations of active components.)
\end{itemize}


  \section*{Proposing Solutions to Mitigate Parasitic Effects}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Bypass Capacitors}: between the emitter and ground to stabilise gain and minimise the impact of \( r_b \).
    \item \textbf{Feedback Network}: to linearise the gain and reduce sensitivity to base and collector resistance.
    \item \textbf{Compensation Capacitance}: between the collector and base to offset \( C_{out} \). In high-frequency applications it reduces phase shifts caused by \( C_{out} \).
  
\end{itemize}


\section*{Cascade to achieve a higher overall gain
}
\subsection*{Design Process of CE-CC\cite{CascadingAmplifier}}

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.18\textheight]{CE-CC.png}
    \caption{CE-CC Cascaded Amplifier Schematics}
    \label{fig:CE-CC Cascaded Amplifier}
\end{figure}

\textbf{CE (Q1)} acts as the primary amplifying stage with voltage gain. \textbf{CC (Q2)} buffers the amplified signal, providing low output impedance suitable for driving loads. The \textbf{coupling capacitor \( C_2 \)} connects the CE and CC stages while blocking DC\cite{BJTAmpDesign}. The \textbf{emitter resistor \( R_6 \)} in Q2 stabilises the output without significantly impacting the voltage gain.

 
\begin{figure}[h!]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.17\textheight]{CE-CC voltage gain.png}
        \caption{Av=-50 Waveform of CE-CC Amplifier.}
        \label{fig:CE-CC Cascaded Amplifier voltage gain}
    \end{figure}
    
Direct coupling between Q1's collector and Q2's base minimises DC shifts \cite{BJT}. Input and output matching are addressed by \( R_2 = 30\,\text{k}\Omega \), which provides sufficient input resistance, while the CC stage \cite{CECCAmp} (Q2) reduces output impedance for better load driving. The emitter bypass \( C_3 \) helps stabilise the AC response\cite{CCAmpDesign}, with minimal oscillations observed. The frequency response remains effective within the desired range, without significant high-frequency peaking. Thermal stability is maintained, as no significant thermal runaway issues were detected during LTspice simulation.


 \begin{figure}[h!]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.25\textheight]{CE-CB schematic.png}
        \caption{CE-CB Cascaded Amplifier with a voltage gain of -130,Optimised inter-stage coupling, input/output matching, and stability}
        \label{fig:CE-CB Cascaded Amplifier}
    \end{figure}


 \begin{figure}[h!]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, height=0.17\textheight]{CE-CB wavefront.png}
        \caption{CE-CB Cascaded Amplifier voltage gain}
        \label{fig:CE-CB Cascaded Amplifier voltage gain}
    \end{figure}
 


\section*{Comparison of CE-CB and CE-CC}

\textbf{Voltage Gain}: The CE-CB \cite{{EE330Lect34}} configuration demonstrates higher voltage gain (Av= -130) compared to the CE-CC design(Av=-50). The addition of the CB stage (Q2) boosts the voltage gain even further. In contrast, the CE-CC design emphasizes current gain with moderate voltage gain.

\textbf{Frequency Response}: Through AC analysis,  CE-CB  amplifier shown a wider bandwidth compared to CE-CC. The CB stage \cite{CascodeAmplifier} contributes to improved high-frequency performance due to its low input capacitance, reduce parasitic effects.

\textbf{Input/Output Matching}: The CE stage (Q1) provides Av, and the CB stage(Q2) follows with Ai and low Zin, making it suitable for high-frequency applications. Both offer low Zout due to the second stage, but the Zout of the CE-CB is lower than that of the CE-CC and better for load driving.

Adding Buffer amplifiers can be employed between cascaded stages to improve impedance matching and reduce loading effects. By using an Op-Amp configured as a voltage follower, a high \(Z_{in}\) is inputted to the previous stage, while a low \(Z_{out}\) is inputted to the following stage. It ensures that each amplifier stage can operate with minimal interference from adjacent stages, thereby preserving the voltage levels and gain of each stage.

\textbf{Stability}: CE-CB shows stable performance without oscillations, because \( C_3 \), \( C_1 \), and \( C_2 \) manage the AC response and prevent DC offsets.

\textbf{Application Suitability}:

CE-CB is suited for higher voltage gain and wide bandwidth (e.g, RF amplifiers), while CE-CC is ideal for impedance matching and current buffering (e.g., audio amplifiers or driving low-impedance loads).
 

 

\section{Push-Pull Class AB Power Amplifier\cite{ECE354Lab3}}
RMS reflects the true effective value of an AC signal and is equivalent to the DC voltage or current that would deliver the same power to a load, providing an accurate measure of signal power \cite{SoundScapeHQ_ABClass}.

