    \label{fig:push_pull_ab}
\end{figure}

 



 


\begin{equation}
A_v = \frac{V_{out, \text{RMS}}}{V_{in, \text{RMS}}} = \frac{1.8971 \, \text{V}}{2.1207 \, \text{V}} \approx 0.8946
\end{equation}

 This push-pull Class AB power amplifier \cite{ClassABAmplifier}is designed with near-unity gain to primarily achieve current gain and power amplification without significant voltage amplification. It is optimised for delivering high current to the load while maintaining a low output impedance. This configuration allows it to function as a buffer, transferring the input signal to the output with minimal voltage amplification but with a substantial increase in current driving capability.

\begin{equation}
A_i = \frac{I_{\text{out}}}{I_{\text{in}}} = \frac{40.375 \text{ mA}}{584.31 \text{ µA}} \approx 69.08
\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
P_{\text{in}} = V_{\text{in, RMS}} \times I_{\text{in, RMS}} = 2.1 \, \text{V} \times 536 \, \mu\text{A} = 1.1 \, \text{mW}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
P_{\text{out}} = V_{\text{out, RMS}} \times I_{\text{out, RMS}} = 1.9 \, \text{V} \times 40\, \text{mA} = 77 \, \text{mW}
\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
G_P = \frac{P_{\text{out}}}{P_{\text{in}}} = \frac{76.6156 \, \text{mW}}{1.138 \, \text{mW}} \approx 67.36
\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
   P_{\text{DC}} = V_{\text{DC}} \times I_{\text{DC, ac}} \cite{PANotes} = 12 \, \text{V} \times 18.174 \, \text{mA} \approx  = 218 \, \text{mW}
 \end{equation}
 
 \begin{equation}
P_{\text{loss}} = P_{\text{DC}} - P_{\text{out}} \cite{ECE331Lab3} = 218 \, \text{mW} - 77 \, \text{mW} \approx 141 \, \text{mW}
 \end{equation}
 \subsection*{2. Sources of Power Loss}
Transistor conduction losses result in power being lost as heat, and in Class AB \cite{AB}, quiescent current is used to minimise crossover distortion but increases power consumption. Voltage drops across components, such as the forward voltage in diodes (D1 and D2) and base-emitter voltage drops in transistors, also contribute to the losses\cite{AnalogDevicesLab14}. A significant portion of power is dissipated as heat, which is typical in power amplifiers around 65\% of the power being lost as non-useful energy, primarily as heat.


 
 \begin{equation}
\text{Efficiency}\cite{RFPowerEfficiency} = \frac{P_{\text{out}}}{P_{\text{DC}}} \% = \frac{76.6156 \, \text{mW}}{218 \, \text{mW}}\% \approx 35.14\%
 \end{equation}
   

\section*{Total Harmonic Distortion (THD)}
\textbf{FFT Analysis  \cite{FFT}}:
Set the FFT parameters to view the first few harmonics (up to 10 kHz).The fundamental frequency at 1 kHz shows a peak amplitude of approximately 1.0 V.
 

\textbf{Harmonics}:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{2nd Harmonic (2 kHz)}: Amplitude of 0.03 V
    \item \textbf{3rd Harmonic (3 kHz)}: Amplitude of 0.02 V
    \item \textbf{4th Harmonic (4 kHz)}: Amplitude of 0.01 V
    \item Higher-order harmonics are present but with significantly lower amplitudes.
\end{itemize}

\begin{equation}
\text{THD} \cite{IEEE} = \frac{\sqrt{V_2^2 + V_3^2 + V_4^2 + \ldots}}{V_1} \times 100\%  \approx 3.7\%
\end{equation}

\section*{Observations}
This level is consistent. Crossover distortion and non-linearities caused by imperfect transistor matching and standard biasing with diodes. For further THD reduction, refining the biasing network and adding feedback or using complementary driver circuits. 

 \section{Conclusion}

Through detailed theoretical calculations and LTspice simulations of voltage gain, input and output impedances, noise behaviour, and frequency response, we confirmed that the amplifier met the target gain of 20 dB and operated as expected in terms of stability and accuracy. While, as expected, there were deviations between theoretical predictions and simulation outcomes due to real-world parasitic effects and noise, this highlights the importance of accounting for non-idealities in practical design. This analysis highlighted the significance of concepts such as impedance matching, feedback networks, and parasitic components. 

 Potential improvements to the amplifier design include enhancing thermal stability, such as incorporating heat sinks or thermally stable components, shielded layouts, and Miller Compensation to address gain roll-off and phase distortion. Additionally, the use of negative feedback can further stabilize the amplifier and reduce harmonic distortion, and unity gain buffers can be used for impedance matching when cascading.



